This is a personal introductory R notebook created for the purpose of enhancing my knowledge and skills in R, and more generally, statistical programming.

Introduction

In this notebook, I will be investigating the relationship between the battery capacity of modern mobile phones, and the other specifications of the same phone—such as:

  • Front and rear camera resolution (megapixels)
  • Screen height and width
  • Weight
  • Number of processor cores
  • Internal memory and RAM, etc.

The battery capacity of a mobile phone is intuitively dependent upon some of these variables, such as the number of processor cores (since more cores will consume more power). However, for other variables such as the dimensions and weight of a mobile phone, this relationship may not be as clear.

As such, this notebook aims to provide exploratory analysis of the specifications of the phone, how they correlate with each other, and the battery capacity—as well as modeling the relationship.

Linear modeling

As the variable being modeled (battery capacity) is a real-valued number, the linear model seemed most applicable to this scenario. This is ideal since linear models are often used as a simple introduction to programming in R, using functions or packages such as lm or glmnet.

There are many resources dedicated to the teaching of linear models and linear regression, so I will not cover this to its full extent.

Through linear regression, we will attempt to learn a model that expresses the battery capacity of a mobile phone as a linear combination of its specifications—that is:

\[\text{Capacity}=\theta_0+\theta_1\text{FrontCam}+\theta_2\text{BackCam}+\cdots+\theta_{n-1}\text{Weight}+\theta_n\text{RAM}\] Where the specifications are the explanatory variables for our linear model, and the battery capacity is the output variable.

Dataset and specifications

As expected, a mobile phone may have many specifications that its battery capacity might be dependent upon (some examples given above).

The particular dataset we will be dealing with is the Mobile Price Classification dataset from Kaggle, by Abhishek Sharma. This dataset is designed for modeling mobile phone prices, but since the price variable is not real-valued, I opted for battery capacity as the output variable.

The dataset consists of instances of 22 variables (including the battery capacity and ID):

Name Type Description

For our purposes, the id and price_range variables are not necessary—reducing the dataset to the battery capacity output variable and 19 explanatory specification variables.

Exploratory analysis of the training set

To understand the extent to which the variables of the dataset correlate with each other, our first step is to visualize the correlation matrix of the training data.

# Correlation plot of all variables (including output)
ggcorr(cor(train), label=TRUE, label_size=3, label_round=2, label_alpha=TRUE, hjust=0.85)

As evident from the correlation plot, there are a number of very highly-correlated explanatory variables—namely the pairs:

  • px_height and px_width: Mobile phone resolutions are normally selected from a fixed number of commonly used options for dimensions such as 480×800, 640×1136, 720×1280, 750×1334, 1080×1920, and 1440×2560.
  • sc_h and sc_w: It is intuitive that an increase in phone screen height necessitates an increase in width—barring exceptional cases such as the BlackBerry Passport or older narrow Nokia phones.
  • pc and fc: A phone with a very high megapixel primary camera is unlikely to have a significantly low megapixel front camera, nor higher than the primary camera. This pattern seems to hold for most phones except those with far better primary camera. One example of such a phone is the Nokia Lumia 1020, with a 41-megapixel primary camera and a 1.2-megapixel front camera. In comparison, the HTC One has a 4-megapixel primary camera and a 2.1-megapixel front camera.
  • four_g and three_g: All 4G phones will work on 3G networks, which is why these to variables are highly correlated. However, note that it is not the case that 3G phones work on 4G networks.

For simplicity of our model, we will remove the px_width, sc_w, fc and four_g variables from our training and test sets, in accordance to the explanations above. This will help our model avoid any problems due to multicollinearity, such as instability in the estimated parameters (weights):

# Remove variables from training set
train$px_width <- NULL
train$sc_w <- NULL
train$fc <- NULL
train$four_g <- NULL

# Remove variables from test set
test$px_width <- NULL
test$sc_w <- NULL
test$fc <- NULL
test$four_g <- NULL

# Inspect modified training data
print(train)
# Re-display the correlation matrix for the modified training data
ggcorr(cor(train), label=TRUE, label_size=3, label_round=2, label_alpha=TRUE, hjust=0.85, limits=FALSE)

The adjusted scale now allows us to more clearly understand the correlations of the variables—especially the correlations of battery_power with the explanatory variables.

Interestingly, there appears to be relatively strong negative correlations with dual_sim, n_cores and sc_h.

  • dual_sim: Dual-SIM phones normally would consume more power than their single-SIM counterpart. As explained here, dual-SIM phones can often have both SIMs active, which would consume more power. As a result, it would be expected to see at least a very weak positive correlation with battery_power, but it appears to be a negative one.
  • n_cores: The number of processor cores would perhaps be expected to be one of the more influencing factors on the battery power of a phone, since the processor is the main component of a phone, and likely consumes the most power. However, with this data, this correlation appears to be a relatively strong negative one, which is very dubious.
  • sc_h: Considering the fact that there are many older phones which are tall but with lower battery power, such as Nokia XpressMusic 5310, a negative correlation might be expected. However, the actual screen heights of such phones are still small, as the keyboards generally occupied most of the space on the phone. Another factor to consider is that screen heights may not have changed much in the last few years, but smartphones have gotten wider, and thus are still able to support larger batteries whilst maintaining the same height as older phones.

Training the linear models

We will consider four forms of linear regression for the training of the models:

  • Unregularized regression (baseline)
  • \(L_1\)-regularized (LASSO) regression
  • \(L_2\)-regularized (Ridge) regression
  • ElasticNet-regularized regression

Unregularized (Basic) regression

In unregularized linear regression, we simply find the optimal weights that minimise the cost function \(C(\boldsymbol{\theta})\), which is given as the residual sum-squared error function (RSS): \[ \begin{align} C(\boldsymbol{\theta}) &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\hat{y}^{(i)}\right)^2\\ &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2 \end{align} \] Making the minimization problem for the optimal weights: \[ \begin{align} \hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}} &=\arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\theta}\in\boldsymbol{\Theta}}C(\boldsymbol{\theta})\\ &=\arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\theta}\in\boldsymbol{\Theta}}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2 \end{align} \] The glm function solves this minimization problem and fits a linear model with the optimal weights:

# Fit a linear model
basic.lm <- glm(train.y ~ train.X)

# View the weights
basic.weights <- basic.lm$coefficients
print(basic.weights)

Evaluation

The goodness of fit for a linear model can be evaluated with the root mean squared error (RMSE) function, which is a similar measure to RSS: \[ \begin{align} \text{RMSE} &=\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\hat{y}^{(i)}\right)^2}\\ &=\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2} \end{align} \] This can easily be calculated for the dataset with a custom function:

# Function for calculating the root mean squared error
rmse <- function(y_pred, y) return(sqrt(mean((y_pred-y)^2)))
# Calculate the RMSE training error
basic.train_rmse <- rmse(predict(basic.lm, newdata=list(X=train.X)), train.y)
cat(sprintf("Training error (RMSE): %s\n", basic.train_rmse))
Training error (RMSE): 437.317934378211
# Calculate the RMSE test error
basic.test_rmse <- rmse(predict(basic.lm, newdata=list(X=test.X)), test.y)
cat(sprintf("Test error (RMSE): %s\n", basic.test_rmse))
Test error (RMSE): 434.465861452291

\(L_1\)-regularized (LASSO) regression

Regularization of linear regression problems aims to reduce the complexity of a model, making it overfit to the training data less.

This is done by modifying the cost function with an additional regularization term. In the case of \(L_1\)-regularized linear regression, this term comes in the form of the \(L_1\)-norm (also known as Manhattan distance): \[ \begin{align} C(\boldsymbol{\theta}) &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\hat{y}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\color{blue}{\sum_{i=1}^n |\theta_i|}\\ &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\color{blue}{||\boldsymbol{\theta}||_1} \end{align} \] The minimization problem now incorporates the additional \(\lambda\) variable, which controls how much penalization there is to the RSS function. \(\lambda\) is often chosen through cross-validation to minimise a particular measure of fit—in this case, mean squared error (MSE), which is the square of the previously seen RMSE.

# Cross-validated tuning parameter search (MSE)
# NOTE: alpha=1 corresponds to L1 regularization
lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(train.X, train.y, alpha=1, type.measure="mse", nfolds=25, standardize=TRUE)

# Visualize the varying lambda values and their measures of fit
plot(lasso.cv)

The value represented by the rightmost dotted line is the (log) lambda that created the most regularized model such that error is within one standard error of the minimum. This can be accessed as lasso.cv$lambda.1se.

The value represented by the leftmost dotted line is the lambda that created the model such that the error was minimized. This can be accessed as lasso.cv$lambda.min. This is the lambda that we will use to fit our regularized linear model.

We can retrieve the optimal \(\lambda\) from this cv.glmnet object:

# Retrieve the optimal lambda selected from the cross-validation
lasso.lambda <- lasso.cv$lambda.min
cat(sprintf("Optimum lambda: %s\n",lasso.lambda))
Optimum lambda: 7.55380749973438

Training the regularized linear model and viewing the weights:

# Fit a linear model with the cross-validated lambda parameter
lasso.lm <- glmnet(train.X, train.y, alpha=1, lambda=lasso.lambda)

# View the regularized weights
lasso.weights <- coef(lasso.lm)
print(lasso.weights)

LASSO is able to shrink the weights of features which are irrelevant to the model, to zero—as seen with the weights of explanatory variables blue, clock_speed, int_memory, mobile_wt, px_height, ram, three_g, touch_screen and wifi, being reduced to zero. This effectively makes LASSO a form of feature selection prior to training the model.

If we look back at the correlation matrix, we can see that LASSO did indeed keep all of the features which had a high absolute-value correlation, like dual_sim, n_cores and sc_h, along with a few other features.

\(L_2\)-regularized (Ridge) regression

In \(L_2\) regularized least square problems, the regularization term is in the form of the squared \(L_2\) norm (Euclidean distance):

\[ \begin{align} C(\boldsymbol{\theta}) &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\hat{y}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\color{blue}{\sum_{i=1}^n \theta_i^2}\\ &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\color{blue}{||\boldsymbol{\theta}||_2^2} \end{align} \] To find the optimal \(\lambda\), we can use cv.glmnet again:

# Cross-validated tuning parameter search (MSE)
# NOTE: alpha=0 corresponds to L2 regularization
ridge.cv <- cv.glmnet(train.X, train.y, alpha=0, type.measure="mse", nfolds=25, standardize=TRUE)

# Visualize the varying lambda values and their measures of fit
plot(ridge.cv)

Retrieving the optimal \(\lambda\):

# Retrieve the optimal lambda selected from the cross-validation
ridge.lambda <- ridge.cv$lambda.min
cat(sprintf("Optimum lambda: %s\n", ridge.lambda))
Optimum lambda: 1704.90925088544

Training the regularized linear model and viewing the weights:

# Fit a linear model with the cross-validated lambda parameter
ridge.lm <- glmnet(train.X, train.y, lambda=ridge.lambda, alpha=0)

# View the regularized weights
ridge.weights <- coef(ridge.lm)
print(ridge.weights)

Unlike LASSO, Ridge regression will not shrink any weights to zero (as seen above), it instead treats all explanatory variables as having some level of contribution to the output variable. However, it is still capable of reducing weights to very small numbers that are essentially negligible.

ElasticNet-regularized regression

ElasticNet regularization is a method that combines both the \(L_1\) and \(L_2\) norms to form a cost function that is a compromise of both functions. This allows for a regularization method that comes with a combination of benefits of both norms, and makes the disadvantages of either norm less significant.

This is done through the introduction of a mixing parameter \(\alpha\), which controls the weight of the penalty on either norm:

\[ \begin{align} C(\boldsymbol{\theta}) &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\hat{y}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\Bigg(\alpha\overbrace{\sum_{i=1}^n |\theta_i|}^{L_1}+\frac{1-\alpha}{2}\overbrace{\sum_{i=1}^n\theta_i^2 }^{L_2}\ \Bigg)\\ &=\sum_{i=1}^n\left(y^{(i)}-\boldsymbol{\theta}^\mathsf{T} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}\right)^2+\lambda\left(\alpha||\boldsymbol{\theta}||_1+\frac{1-\alpha}{2}||\boldsymbol{\theta}||_2\right) \end{align} \]

For example, \(\alpha=1\) corresponds to \(L_1\) (LASSO) regression and \(\alpha=0\) corresponds to \(L_2\) (Ridge) regression. Anything between these two values is a mixture of the two.

However, the introduction of a second parameter makes cross-validation more complicated. cva.glmnet allows us to find an optimal \(\alpha\) and \(\lambda\):

# Vector of alpha values to cross-validate on
alphas <- seq(0, 1, len = 12)^3
print(alphas)
 [1] 0.0000000000 0.0007513148 0.0060105184 0.0202854996 0.0480841473
 [6] 0.0939143501 0.1622839970 0.2577009767 0.3846731781 0.5477084899
[11] 0.7513148009 1.0000000000
# Cross-validated tuning parameter search (MSE)
elastic.cva <- cva.glmnet(train.X, train.y, alpha=alphas, type.measure="mse", nfolds=25, standardize=TRUE)

# Visualize the varying lambda values and their measures of fit for each alpha
plot(elastic.cva, 
     main=c("MSE functions for varying mixing parameters (alpha) over a cross-validation grid search"))
legend('topright', legend=round(alphas, digits=5), title=expression(alpha), 
       col=topo.colors(length(alphas)), lty=1)

Despite the cva.glmnet function being able to perform a grid search over \(\lambda\) and \(\alpha\) for cross-validation, there appears to be no simple way to retrieve the optimal parameters from the cva.glmnet object.

Therefore we must manually iterate through the individual cv.glmnet objects (one for each possible alpha value) stored within the cva.glmnet object, elastic.cva. Each individual cv.glmnet object can be accessed with elastic.cva$modlist[[i]], where i is an index representing one of the alphas. For example:

# View the first cv.glmnet object, representing the first alpha
summary(elastic.cva$modlist[[1]])

Retrieving the optimal \(\alpha\) and \(\lambda\):

idx <- -1 # Index of the model with the lowest MSE
min_mse <- .Machine$integer.max # The lowest MSE

for (i in 1:length(alphas)) {
  # The current alpha
  alpha.i <- alphas[i]
  # The lambda for the current alpha, that minimises mean CV error
  lambda.i <- elastic.cva$modlist[[i]]$lambda.min
  # Create a model with alpha and the corresponding lambda
  model.i <- glmnet(train.X, train.y, alpha=alpha.i, lambda=lambda.i)
  # Calculate the mean squared error for the model
  mse.i <- rmse(predict(model.i, train.X), train.y)^2
  
  # Update variables if the current MSE is less than previous minimum MSE
  if (mse.i < min_mse) {
    idx <- i
    min_mse <- mse.i
  }
}

# Optimum cv.glmnet object
elastic.cv <- elastic.cva$modlist[[idx]]
# View the optimum alpha
elastic.alpha <- alphas[idx]
cat(sprintf("Optimum alpha: %s\n", elastic.alpha))
Optimum alpha: 0.257700976709241
# View the optimum lambda
elastic.lambda <- elastic.cv$lambda.min
cat(sprintf("Optimum lambda: %s\n", elastic.lambda))
Optimum lambda: 29.3122967409518
# Visualize the varying lambda values and their measures of fit, for the optimal alpha
plot(elastic.cv)

# Training the linear model

# View the regularized weights

Model comparison

With a relatively small training and test set, the measures of fit for each model might not vary much, but there were indeed some significant differences in the RMSE values for both training and test error that we can consider for model comparison:

# Dataframe representing the train/test RMSEs of the models
comparison <- data.frame(
  Error=rep(c("Training", "Test"), each=4),
  Models=c("Basic", "L1", "L2", "ElasticNet"),
  RMSE=round(c(basic.train_rmse, lasso.train_rmse, ridge.train_rmse, elastic.train_rmse,
         basic.test_rmse, lasso.test_rmse, ridge.test_rmse, elastic.test_rmse), digits=3)
)

# Grouped bar plot for the comparison of train/test RMSEs of each model
ggplot(data=comparison, aes(x=Models, y=RMSE, fill=Error)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge") +
  geom_text(aes(label=RMSE), hjust=1.25, color="white", position = position_dodge(0.9), size=3.5) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Paired") +

Training error

According to the RMSE measure of fit, in order of performance on the training set from best to worst (least to most RMSE):

Model RMSE Comments
Basic \(437.318\) Unregularized linear regression is expected to perform best on the training set, because not regularizing means that the model fits the training set as best as possible, without having to adjust some weights to make the model simpler, through regularization.
\(L_2\) \(437.912\) Unlike \(L_1\)-regularized linear regression, Ridge still ensures that every feature contributes to the model—it will not shrink weights to zero. This is useful when the output variable actually depends on all (or most) of the features, but we saw earlier with the correlation matrix that this was not the case.
ElasticNet \(437.951\) Performs slightly better than Ridge regression, likely as a result of the benefits of the additional \(L_1\) norm regularization term.
\(L_1\) \(438.567\) As explained previously, the ability for LASSO to shrink the weights of irrelevant features to zero allows for a form of feature selection which makes the linear model more simple and less overfitting, but at a sacrifice of not fitting to the training data as best as possible.

Linear model RMSE Comments
\(L_1\) \(431.821\) Tied with ElasticNet.
Expected to perform well since there were many features which LASSO appropriately disregarded and shrank their terms to zero, thus creating a simpler and less overfitted model.

Future improvements

Principal component (PC) regression is commonly used when there are issues with multicollinearity in the dataset.

In PC regression, instead of modeling the output variable as a linear combination of the explanatory variables, we first perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the dataset, and use the chosen number of new principal components with high variances (eigenvalues) as the new regressors. This once again acts as a form of feature selection, just like how \(L_1\) or ElasticNet regularized regression can select features.
